          "id": "medquad-chunk-e6e0817d5052778e",
          "title": "What causes Gum (Periodontal) Disease ?",
          "content": "Gum disease, also known as periodontal disease, is mainly caused by dental plaque. This plaque is a sticky film made up of bacteria that forms on your teeth. To keep your mouth healthy, it is very important to brush your teeth at least twice a day and to floss daily. These practices help remove plaque before it can cause problems. If plaque is not cleaned away properly, it can harden into tartar. Tartar is much tougher than plaque and cannot be removed by brushing alone. This is why it is essential to visit a dentist or dental hygienist for professional cleanings, as they have the tools and expertise to safely remove tartar buildup.\nTo prevent gum disease, you should also have regular dental check-ups. These visits allow your dentist to clean your teeth thoroughly and check for any early signs of gum disease or other dental issues. Remember, taking care of your teeth is not just about having a bright smile; it’s also about keeping your gums healthy and preventing serious health problems in the future.\nContext recap: Gum disease, also known as periodontal disease, is mainly caused by dental plaque. This plaque is a sticky film made up of bacteria that forms on your teeth. To keep your mouth healthy, it is very important to brush your teeth at least twice a day and to floss daily. These practices help remove plaque before it can cause problems.\nWhy this matters: What causes Gum (Periodontal) Disease ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Geriatric Medicine (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Gum disease, also known as periodontal disease, is mainly caused by dental plaque. This plaque is a sticky film made up of bacteria that forms on your teeth. To keep your mouth healthy, it is very important to brush your teeth at least twice a day and to floss daily. These practices help remove plaque before it can cause problems.\nWhy this matters: What causes Gum (Periodontal) Disease ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Geriatric Medicine (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.\nContext recap: Gum disease, also known as periodontal disease, is mainly caused by dental plaque. This plaque is a sticky film made up of bacteria that forms on your teeth. To keep your mouth healthy, it is very important to brush your teeth at least twice a day and to floss daily. These practices help remove plaque before it can cause problems.\nWhy this matters: What causes Gum (Periodontal) Disease ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Geriatric Medicine (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
