          "id": "medquad-chunk-c1528e13e9e4acd1",
          "title": "How many people are affected by Hearing Loss ?",
          "content": "Heart attacks can present a variety of symptoms, and not everyone experiences the same signs. It’s important to recognize that heart attacks can start slowly and may not always involve the dramatic chest pain often depicted in movies. Some heart attacks may occur without any noticeable symptoms, which are referred to as silent heart attacks. Here are some common symptoms to be aware of:\n1. **Chest Pain or Discomfort**: The most common symptom is discomfort in the center of the chest that lasts for more than a few minutes or comes and goes. This discomfort can feel like pressure, squeezing, fullness, or pain. It may also be mistaken for indigestion or heartburn.\n2. **Upper Body Discomfort**: Pain or discomfort may also radiate to other areas, such as one or both arms, the back, neck, jaw, or stomach.\n3. **Shortness of Breath**: This can occur with or without chest discomfort and may happen before any other symptoms.\n4. **Other Symptoms**: Additional signs may include cold sweats, nausea, vomiting, light-headedness, dizziness, fatigue, and lack of energy.\nIt’s crucial to understand the difference between angina and a heart attack. Angina is chest pain that occurs when the heart muscle doesn’t receive enough oxygen-rich blood, usually during physical activity. Angina pain typically lasts only a few minutes and goes away with rest. If you suspect you are having a heart attack or if your angina symptoms do not improve with medication, seek emergency help immediately by calling 9-1-1.\nContext recap: Heart attacks can present a variety of symptoms, and not everyone experiences the same signs. It’s important to recognize that heart attacks can start slowly and may not always involve the dramatic chest pain often depicted in movies. Some heart attacks may occur without any noticeable symptoms, which are referred to as silent heart attacks. Here are some common symptoms to be aware of:\n1.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by Hearing Loss ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Geriatric Medicine (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: Heart attacks can present a variety of symptoms, and not everyone experiences the same signs. It’s important to recognize that heart attacks can start slowly and may not always involve the dramatic chest pain often depicted in movies. Some heart attacks may occur without any noticeable symptoms, which are referred to as silent heart attacks. Here are some common symptoms to be aware of:\n1.\nWhy this matters: How many people are affected by Hearing Loss ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Geriatric Medicine (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
