          "id": "medquad-chunk-728af20bcd4136db",
          "title": "What causes Osteoarthritis ?",
          "content": "As we grow older, the likelihood of developing osteoarthritis tends to increase. This condition is believed to arise from a combination of various factors that originate both from within our bodies and from our environment. Research indicates that approximately 33.6% of individuals who are 65 years old and above, which translates to around 12.4 million people, are affected by osteoarthritis.\nOsteoarthritis is often the result of many years of wear and tear on our joints. This wear primarily impacts the cartilage, which is the soft tissue that cushions the ends of our bones where they meet in the joints. When osteoarthritis develops, the cartilage can begin to fray, wear down, and deteriorate over time. This deterioration can lead to pain and stiffness in the affected joints, making everyday activities more challenging.\nSeveral factors can contribute to the onset of osteoarthritis. For instance, if a joint has been injured in the past, putting too much stress on it can exacerbate the problem. Additionally, if the joints are not aligned properly, this misalignment can lead to uneven wear on the cartilage. Another significant factor is excess weight; carrying more weight than is healthy can put additional strain on our joints, particularly those that bear weight, like the knees and hips.\nBy understanding the causes of osteoarthritis, we can take proactive steps to care for our joints as we age. This might include maintaining a healthy weight, engaging in regular low-impact exercise to strengthen the muscles around our joints, and being mindful of any previous injuries to prevent further damage. Taking these steps can help us maintain our mobility and quality of life as we grow older.\nContext recap: As we grow older, the likelihood of developing osteoarthritis tends to increase. This condition is believed to arise from a combination of various factors that originate both from within our bodies and from our environment. Research indicates that approximately 33.6% of individuals who are 65 years old and above, which translates to around 12.4 million people, are affected by osteoarthritis. Osteoarthritis is often the result of many years of wear and tear on our joints.\nWhy this matters: What causes Osteoarthritis ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Geriatric Medicine (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: As we grow older, the likelihood of developing osteoarthritis tends to increase. This condition is believed to arise from a combination of various factors that originate both from within our bodies and from our environment. Research indicates that approximately 33.6% of individuals who are 65 years old and above, which translates to around 12.4 million people, are affected by osteoarthritis. Osteoarthritis is often the result of many years of wear and tear on our joints.\nWhy this matters: What causes Osteoarthritis ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Geriatric Medicine (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
