          "id": "medquad-chunk-097b10cf659d6d0e",
          "title": "What is (are) Surviving Cancer ?",
          "content": "After finishing cancer treatment, it's really important for patients to keep getting follow-up care. This type of care usually involves regular visits to healthcare providers who will check in on the patient's health. During these appointments, doctors will look over the patient's medical history and perform physical exams to see how they are doing. They might also order blood tests and other lab procedures to keep an eye on the patient's health and to check for any signs that the cancer might come back. These follow-up visits are crucial because they help catch any potential problems early on, which can make a big difference in treatment and recovery. Patients should feel encouraged to ask their doctors any questions they have and to seek out more information about what to expect during follow-up care. Staying informed and proactive about health is a key part of the journey after cancer treatment, and there are many resources available to help patients navigate this important phase of their care.\nContext recap: After finishing cancer treatment, it's really important for patients to keep getting follow-up care. This type of care usually involves regular visits to healthcare providers who will check in on the patient's health. During these appointments, doctors will look over the patient's medical history and perform physical exams to see how they are doing. They might also order blood tests and other lab procedures to keep an eye on the patient's health and to check for any signs that the cancer might come back.\nContext recap: After finishing cancer treatment, it's really important for patients to keep getting follow-up care. This type of care usually involves regular visits to healthcare providers who will check in on the patient's health. During these appointments, doctors will look over the patient's medical history and perform physical exams to see how they are doing. They might also order blood tests and other lab procedures to keep an eye on the patient's health and to check for any signs that the cancer might come back.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Surviving Cancer ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Geriatric Medicine (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nContext recap: After finishing cancer treatment, it's really important for patients to keep getting follow-up care. This type of care usually involves regular visits to healthcare providers who will check in on the patient's health. During these appointments, doctors will look over the patient's medical history and perform physical exams to see how they are doing. They might also order blood tests and other lab procedures to keep an eye on the patient's health and to check for any signs that the cancer might come back.\nWhy this matters: What is (are) Surviving Cancer ? helps learners in Science connect ideas from Geriatric Medicine (Medical Curriculum) to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints.",
